This unified Republicans more than it unified Democrats. Democrats are broke. The DNC has no money. Republicans are raising money like I'm not going to say it. They're raising a lot of money. And now they're trying to play all these tricks like they did with Kavanaugh. All of a sudden, Ambassador Sondland gets hit with not one, not two, but three sexual harassment allegations in the middle of all this. And you have Trump over there with Melania looking very striking, meeting with world leaders, fresh off killing Baghdadi and unifying NATO against the Russians. And then you have Adam Schiff passing this scam to little Jerry Nadler, who's supposed to carry it across the finish line. I just don't see how this thing is going to stick. And even swing state Democrats know it because they're whispering about ways to get out of having to vote for this now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But now, Greg, the Democrats are kind of in this box, right? If they don't go forward, their base is going to be furious. But if they do go forward, they could pay the price at the ballot box in the swing states.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think we predicted this, didn't we? We saw this coming. I, for one, hope they continue with this because, you know, it's something to talk about on The Five during the slow days. But I do feel that -- I refuse to be led by the nose by Schiff with these fake little like inquiries, reports and whatnot. It's all -- to your point, it's all much ado about nothing. Something I think I coined. But one thing I want to say about watching Trump today in these meetings: his mantra is they owe us money, right? So, everything he does is on behalf -- he's like, he's our agent. He's America's agent in a meeting. And he's such a jerk, but he's our jerk. Did you see how we dealt with the Canadian -- ?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Trudeau.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He treated him as though he was the manager of a golf course owned by Trump. Can you tell us, what did we work out here? What is it you owe us? And he made -- what's his name again?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Trudeau.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Trudeau is going like, oh, let me go through this. I think we've got to 70 percent. And he's like basically saying, yes, sir. It was like Celebrity Apprentice. I mean, it was interesting to see that everything he does is on behalf of America. He's that uncomfortable person who goes up to somebody and says, you owe us money.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The other side of this was to watch him deal with the French prime minister where you saw, you know, it was to me, like he was lecturing Trump. I thought Trump in that exchange looked like you think that this is about terrorism. No, I think it's about not fear because you didn't pay me the money. Actually, you guys are paying -- but we're getting other people and we've done so much better. And NATO is going to fold. And he's like what is NATO for. Is it for terrorists or is it for Russians? And the president could not agree.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, but I do think that perhaps Macron had a little -- I don't know if he planned it or not, but the president's been quite critical of NATO. Then Macron was critical of NATO, called it braindead in the presence that. How dare you say that? NATO's amazing.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But now they have the president saying NATO's amazing, so maybe everybody wins. All right, shockwaves throughout the 2020 field. Kamala Harris drops out of the presidential race. More to come on that state with "The Five."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Time for our 2020 roundup. First up, a major shakeup in the 2020 field. California Senator Kamala Harris has dropped out of the race. She told supporters in an email that she is "not a billionaire, and therefore can't fund her own campaign." Ms. Harris entered the race as a major force on the campaign trail. You recall she had a huge crowd in Oakland. But she failed to capitalize on that early enthusiasm and plummeted in the polls. Here is a look back.

utterances.speaker: SEN. KAMALA HARRIS, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Hey guys, you know what? America does not want to witness a food fight. They want to know how we're going to put food on their table. There was a little girl in California who was part of the second class to integrate her public schools, and she was bussed to school every day. And that little girl was me.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: But the way --

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: Join me -- join me in saying that his Twitter account should be shut down.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Now, let's figure out --

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: No? We need to have Medicare for all. That's just the bottom line. Who of us have not had that situation where you've got to wait for approval and the doctor says, "Well, I don't know if your insurance company is going to cover this"? Let's eliminate all of that. Let's move on.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Have you ever smoked?

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: I have.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: And I -- and I --

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: [UNINTELLIGIBLE]

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: And I inhaled. I did inhale. [laughs] It was a long time ago, but yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, one of the things that she said in an interview, I think it was for The Axio [spelled phonetically] says she wonders if the elephant in the room is that America is not ready for a black [UNINTELLIGIBLE] to be president.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think that's what people say when they fail. They blame something superficial. And I think America was ready for it because she was one of the most hyped candidates, her and Beto. They got all the hype, and now both of them flamed out long before Iowa. She has no core. I read the New York Times article about her. She couldn't think of the name for her own memoir so she poll tested the name of her memoir. She literally poll tested herself. She doesn't know who she was. And she couldn't run her campaign, very dysfunctional. There's an old saying, "If you can't run a campaign, you can't run the country." And --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Is that your saying?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- two major mistakes that she made.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think he directed that at you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, I know, I'm getting a lot of those.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You might have heard that before in Washington, Dana. She -- the two major mistakes I think she made when she said, "Oh, we'll just -- we'll just get rid of it," when she was talking about private insurance. And then she didn't capitalize when she had the momentum when she knocked out Joe. The second debate, she just totally disappeared, and then so did her poll numbers.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, by the way, Dana, picking up on what Jesse just said, if you were looking at this through a hard-eyed political lens, you might say she wasn't a good candidate, and she didn't run a good campaign.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, then them's the breaks. I mean, that's it basically, the two basic things that you need. And I also think that this is a reminder. Senators usually do not make presidential candidates, and they rarely win elections, or I think-- I don't know when the last time was. And if you look at this field, you have a lot of senators. And she managed a terrible campaign. There was so much dissent on the campaign that in the last like six weeks, maybe even eight weeks, there were articles from within the campaign of people saying that they were very unhappy. And you shared some of that on the daily briefing today. No one wants to throw good money after bad. And she -- that's a saying.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. [LAUGHTER]

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Heard that.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm writing that down.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But the other thing I would say, dropping out now spares her further political embarrassment. She's only 55. She'll go back to the Senate, and now I think that you'll see her re -- reinvent herself yet again. But if she wants to run for president, she's going to have to pick a lane and stick in it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, so, Greg, play along with me.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm going to say she never picked a lane.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because I think --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You heard that [UNINTELLIGIBLE]?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. -- that in fact Sanders and Warren are on the left, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And then you have -- in the center, you have the mayor, kind of center left. Then in the very center, you have Biden, Klobuchar, Booker maybe.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And on -- and then you have the billionaires, Steyer and Bloomberg. But where -- where -- what was the lane for her?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think that she didn't try hard enough to find that lane. In fact, I don't -- I felt that she thought any effort was beneath her. I'm actually -- this is the first time I heard about this, how she said that America wasn't ready for her. What a jerk, because America as a population is willing to get behind everybody and everybody. They had a two-term black president. Hillary got more -- got the popular vote.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And for her to say the reason why I lost is because of you, screw you. You are a big jerk. Now, I had high hopes for her, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yep.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I had high -- -- I was one of the first people that -- no. Now, I can't stand this person because what she did -- blaming the American public, because you're a failure, because you didn't work hard enough, that is so pathetic. I mean, she had -- she basically had ticked all the identity boxes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She was a female, black, young leftist, and she couldn't -- she couldn't --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Don't forget former prosecutor.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Former -- because she couldn't galvanize that –

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- to a winning campaign, that is on her.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It ain't on the public. I'm glad she's gone.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: And you know who she couldn't galvanize the vote with? Black voters --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: -- in South Carolina. I talked to a number of black Democrats in Virginia who said, "There's no way we're vote for her because she's done more damage to the black community than anybody else on that stage with her record as a prosecutor." And she was never able to defend that. She was using it as a way to go after Trump. But when she was pressed on it, she could never explain why she did the things that she did. She was a follower, not a leader. She got very insecure with her positions. I remember watching her in that series of town halls that CNN did, and Bernie Sanders came out first in the hour before her and said that felons, including prisoners, should be able to vote from prison, including the Boston Bomber. And she's like, "Yeah, sure, maybe." So she changed her position based on what her peers were saying rather than having her own solid foundation of what she believed in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, I don't think she was that folksy, you know -- you know, and even on the point that you just made --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: No. It was like a fake folksy, and her laugh, and she just --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: -- tried too hard. I mean she was a phony.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I like her and Greg --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: And she couldn't [UNINTELLIGIBLE].

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- all credit to Greg, Greg was a big fan. He thought she was going to be the --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I was stupid.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Huh? No, no.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm an idiot.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no. All right, that's --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She betrayed me.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You've got to leave that to me. All right. Next, there will be no malarkey for this next story. Joe Biden, once again denying that he's looking for a game-changing endorsement from his former boss, President Obama, even if the field narrows to just three people. Here's what he told Politico: "No, because everyone knows I'm close with him. I don't need an Obama endorsement." Katie?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes, he does. I mean, his entire campaign is based on his record with Barack Obama, and if he can't get him to endorse you, then what does that mean? But also, I guess maybe he doesn't. Hillary Clinton got Obama's endorsement and still lost, so people voted for President Obama. They don't necessarily vote for people who are endorsed by him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think he's going to be begging for an endorsement if there's a brokered convention, which it very well could be. If you have all these people that don't hit the delegate threshold, you get the Obamas and the Clintons in a back room at the DNC in Wisconsin, and they're going to have to pick a ticket, and Biden's going to be on his knees begging Barack, "Pick me."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But, Dana, I think the questions are coming about right now, not even convention time.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He's not going to. I've said it a hundred times. Barack Obama is not going to endorse –

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- any of these candidates. Put it aside. Now, he -- he might decide at a brokered convention, it seems like there's no question. If Bernie Sanders is the possible winner of the nomination, absolutely, President Obama will come in. He's got one shot to be a king maker or a peace maker. He's not going to waste it now.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, just because you have somebody like famous in your phone and you go, "Hey, yeah," just show your friends that, "Hey, I can call him anytime." No, you can't. I've tried that drunk. It's a very -- [LAUGHTER] Just because -- like he -- you guys hung out together for eight years, that's not enough.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, no, it's Greg again.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No. [LAUGHTER]

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: President, yes, exactly.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Decline.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But, you know, if he did endorse now, Dana, it would be big news. But I just don't see it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He's not going to.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: It's too risky for him to do it now.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It wasn't what?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's not necessary, too.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yeah, risky.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I mean, you have to win on your own. Finally, the Democrats are starting to go after each other in this primary. Let's enjoy it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're a sick person.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Amen.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my goodness. Prince Andrew's accuser details alleged, shocking abuse in the Jeffrey Epstein scandal. That interview, right here, next on The Five.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: President Trump meeting with the major British royalty today, including the queen and Prince Charles. But one royal absence drawing attention is Prince Andrew. He's still facing fallout on his connection to convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. Last night, Virginia Giuffre, the woman who claims she was forced to have sex with Prince Andrew when she was only 17, spoke with the BBC.

utterances.speaker: VIRGINIA GIUFFRE
utterances.utterance: It was disgusting. He wasn't mean or anything, but he got up and he said, "Thanks," and walked out. And I sat there in bed just horrified and ashamed, and felt dirty, and I had to get up and grab a shower. And you know, the next day Ghislaine tells me I did a really good job.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Buckingham Palace is emphatically denying the accusations. All right, Greg, you know, we've covered a lot of these stories in the last year or two.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: [affirmative]

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Women come forward, they make their case, not always in the judicial system, but they make their case. How do you find her presentation?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I didn't watch the whole interview, but I -- to your point, is that this is a public sphere. Sphere?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Sure.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Okay. There's no actual process in this. If you were accused of something, you'd want to be in a courtroom where you could clear your name, if that's one thing we learned. And all these people are denying that they slept with this alleged victim, right? So, wouldn't you want to get into the legal, into the courtroom, and clear your name rather than let this go? Because the problem with the media and the public sphere is that we love the salacious part of the story. But when that story gets cleared, we often don't follow up. If there's -- I mean, one thing we learned in the Me Too movement, that accusations turn into a wide spectrum with the real and the awful, to the vague and confusing, to the Julie Swetnicks, right? It just goes from one -- and it's like, and we never really follow up on this stuff. I would -- I mean, there has to be a legal process to deal with this. Should he be charged with something and then he's arrested? Maybe that's how you do it.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But that's --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And he said he's willing to cooperate with any investigation, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Well, so now over to Scotland Yard, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: If they're going to do anything. But the thing is, they did try to go through the legal process. Epstein was arrested, he was in jail, and then he killed himself, or whatever, killed himself.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Killed himself [UNINTELLIGIBLE]?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, now the victims have no way to get justice because the perpetrator is dead, unless -- and I think the key to a lot of this is Maxwell, Ghislaine Maxwell. There was a story like three weeks ago -- it didn't last very long -- that said that she was talking to the FBI.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I never saw that again, so I don't know if it's true. Or maybe if it was, they decided to quiet it down. But she seems to me the key to a lot of all of this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And this alleged victim claims she had sex with Epstein and Maxwell, Katie.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: -- look, I think that the royal family is doing everything they can to do damage control. It doesn't look good when you're pulling him off of all of -- Prince Andrew -- off of all of his public events. And his interview with the BBC went really poorly. He did not do a good job of defending himself; in fact, he didn't offer any sympathy at all for any of Epstein's victims. The palace has tried to distance themselves, but there is no recourse. I mean, this is the question about victims getting justice somehow. I know that this week the Department -- or, the Department of Justice inspector general, in addition to all the other stuff he's dealing with, has been asked by Republican and Democrat senators to continue and finish his investigation into what happened to Epstein and why, you know, there was no accountability for his whereabouts as one of the most high-profile --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: -- prisoners in the country. Because they've hauled the Bureau of Prisons head up to Capitol Hill a couple of weeks ago and she said, "I'm not going to talk about it because the inspector general is looking into it." So, at the very least, the victims are owed that. And I think that the prince and the family would do well to speak to the FBI so they can say, "We spoke to the authorities. They can take it from here."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: How do you see the media difference between two countries, Juan? You have ABC spiked this story here in this country because of the way that it could possibly expose American royalty, aka Bill Clinton, and juxtapose that with how the BBC's gone after this very doggedly when it involves someone from the royal family over there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, it's a totally different timeframe because in one case you have -- in all cases, let me just say, you have powerful men.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And that goes back to what Greg was talking about, the public sphere. Because guess what? You know, if you see all these powerful, rich, entitled men involved with young women, my gut does not feel sympathy for them. I feel sympathy for these young women. And the young woman, by the way, in this case, Giuffre or whatever, she said she was working as a locker room attendant at Mar-a-Lago, in Trump's property, when Ghislaine Maxwell approached her --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- and then recruits her --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- for these sexual activities.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right. And what we know is that the president, or Donald Trump at the time, kicked out Epstein from Mar-a-Lago after he got wind of it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know. I'm just saying you got a lot of rich --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But we do know that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- you got a lot of rich, powerful men. So, when I saw her interview, I thought -- you know, she said she was vulnerable, she said she was easily led, she felt she wasn't chained or locked in, but these powerful people had such influence over her that she did what she was told. And I just felt sympathy for her. But you're right, it's not a court of law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Year. All right, very interesting. Dictionary.com names this word "existential" as the word of the year.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yay.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Greg's all fired up about that next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I really am.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right. Dictionary.com named 'existential' it's word of the year. Why not? Not because you used it. It's not because anyone in real life has used it since college. Because if you said existential, it meant you weren't a business major. Hoping for a real life. And by real life, I mean a grown-up life with taxes, bills and brats. That word was picked because desk dwelling media types beat it to death.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: The existential scandal that has surrounded the Trump presidency.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: He is an existential threat to those American values.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump is such an existential threat to our democracy.

utterances.speaker: HAKEEM JEFFRIES
utterances.utterance: President Trump is an existential threat to the future of the United States.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: He is an existential threat to the country.

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.utterance: They believe is existential, that they need to unseat President Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Ah, so when faced with good news, just call Trump an existential threat in absence of a real physical threat or should I say a psychological one. Just look at all the measurable stuff, economy, jobs, terror, you see numbers trending positively. That leaves the media with just one option push things that can't be measured to predict gloom and doom. Remember, none of these smarty pants saw the internet as an existential threat to dictionaries or even bother to look up the word in a dictionary. Yet here they are desperately competing for attention while the whole planet ignores them, which is why the Oxford Dictionaries picked Climate Emergency as its word of the year, even though I think it's two. Oxford said its use reflects the ethos, mood or preoccupations of the passing year. Translation: it's what rich elites do as they board planes for a holiday in France. I remember when dictionaries were awesome. They contained words, not the politics of pretentious editors. Now they're just like every other medium full of anxious social climbers straining for relevance. Unlike me, right, Greg? Existential. Existential, existential. Existential, existential. Existential. It's a very overused term. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. Existential. But at least I knew what it meant.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That was good.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I wouldn't have thought you said that --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think I used existential when I was talking about ISIS or ironically, but I think would back in when ISIS was beheading people, I was calling it an existential threat. But I told them to look it up because, you know, I'm not a hypocrite, dammit. Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: [UNINTELLIGIBLE]

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan, is there a word of the year that you would think of as--?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I saw that there was some thought about cancel culture.
